2 SENATE BILL 112
1 Article – State Government
2 Section 9–1A–07(g) and 9–1E–03(a)(1)
3 Annotated Code of Maryland
4 (2021 Replacement Volume and 2025 Supplement)
5 SECTION 1. BE IT ENACTED BY THE GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF MARYLAND,
6 That the Laws of Maryland read as follows:
7 Article – Criminal Law
8 12–115.
9 (A) (1) IN THIS SECTION THE FOLLOWING WORDS HAVE THE MEANINGS
10 INDICATED.
11 (2) “COMMISSION” MEANS THE STATE LOTTERY AND GAMING
12 CONTROL COMMISSION.
13 (3) (I) “INTERACTIVE GAME” MEANS A GAME, CONTEST, OR
14 PROMOTION THAT:
15 1. IS AVAILABLE ON THE INTERNET OR ACCESSIBLE ON
16 A MOBILE PHONE, COMPUTER TERMINAL, OR SIMILAR DEVICE;
17 2. UTILIZES MULTIPLE CURRENCY SYSTEMS OF
18 PAYMENT ALLOWING THE PLAYER TO EXCHANGE THE CURRENCY FOR ANY PRIZE OR
19 AWARD OR CASH OR CASH EQUIVALENTS; AND
20 3. SIMULATES:
21 A. CASINO–STYLE GAMING, SUCH AS SLOT MACHINES,
22 VIDEO POKER, AND TABLE GAMES, INCLUDING BLACKJACK, ROULETTE, CRAPS, AND
23 POKER;
24 B. LOTTERY GAMES, INCLUDING DRAW GAMES, INSTANT
25 WIN GAMES, KENO, AND BINGO; OR
26 C. SPORTS WAGERING.
27 (II) “INTERACTIVE GAME” DOES NOT INCLUDE A GAME THAT
28 SOLELY AWARDS NONCASH PRIZES.

SENATE BILL 112 3
1 (4) “LICENSE” MEANS THE AUTHORITY ISSUED BY THE COMMISSION
2 TO OFFER OR CONDUCT AN ACTIVITY UNDER TITLE 9, SUBTITLE 1A, 1B, 1D, OR 1E
3 OF THE STATE GOVERNMENT ARTICLE.
4 (B) (1) A PERSON MAY NOT OPERATE, CONDUCT, OR PROMOTE AN
5 INTERACTIVE GAME IN THE STATE.
6 (2) AN APPLICANT FOR OR A PERSON HOLDING A LICENSE SHALL
7 REPORT TO THE COMMISSION ANNUALLY ANY BUSINESS RELATIONSHIP WITH A
8 FINANCIAL INSTITUTION, PAYMENT PROCESSOR, GEOLOCATION PROVIDER, GAMING
9 CONTENT SUPPLIER, PLATFORM PROVIDER, OR MEDIA AFFILIATE THAT IS KNOWN
10 TO SUPPORT, OPERATE, CONDUCT, OR PROMOTE AN INTERACTIVE GAME IN THE
11 STATE.
12 (C) (1) A PERSON WHO VIOLATES THIS SECTION IS GUILTY OF A
13 MISDEMEANOR AND ON CONVICTION IS SUBJECT TO IMPRISONMENT NOT
14 EXCEEDING 3 YEARS OR A FINE NOT LESS THAN $10,000 AND NOT EXCEEDING
15 $100,000 OR BOTH.
16 (2) IF A PERSON IS FOUND IN VIOLATION OF THIS SECTION, THE
17 COMMISSION SHALL DENY THE PERSON’S LICENSE APPLICATION OR REVOKE A
18 LICENSE HELD BY THE PERSON.
19 Article – State Government
20 9–1A–07.
21 (G) (1) (I) IN THIS SUBSECTION THE FOLLOWING WORDS HAVE THE
22 MEANINGS INDICATED.
23 (II) “ILLEGAL INTERACTIVE GAMING MARKET” MEANS A
24 JURISDICTION IN WHICH AN INTERACTIVE GAME IS PROHIBITED BY THE LAWS OF
25 THAT JURISDICTION.
26 (III) “INTERACTIVE GAME” HAS THE MEANING STATED IN §
27 12–115 OF THE CRIMINAL LAW ARTICLE.
28 (2) ON APPLICATION FOR A LICENSE UNDER THIS SUBTITLE AND
29 ANNUALLY FOLLOWING THE ISSUANCE OF THE LICENSE, AN APPLICANT OR A
30 LICENSEE SHALL SUBMIT A DISCLOSURE STATING, FOR THE IMMEDIATE PRECEDING
31 12–MONTH PERIOD, THE JURISDICTIONS IN WHICH THE APPLICANT OR LICENSEE
32 OR ANY AFFILIATE OF THE APPLICANT OR LICENSEE DIRECTLY OR INDIRECTLY
33 ACCEPTED REVENUE FROM THE CONDUCT OF AN INTERACTIVE GAME IN AN ILLEGAL
34 INTERACTIVE GAMING MARKET.

4 SENATE BILL 112
1 (3) A MATERIAL MISREPRESENTATION OR OMISSION ON THE
2 DISCLOSURE REQUIRED UNDER PARAGRAPH (2) OF THIS SUBSECTION MAY BE THE
3 BASIS FOR THE COMMISSION TO DENY AN APPLICATION FOR A LICENSE UNDER THIS
4 SUBTITLE OR, IN ACCORDANCE WITH § 9–1A–25 OF THIS SUBTITLE, IMPOSE
5 SANCTIONS ON A LICENSEE AND THE LICENSEE’S OFFICERS AND BOARD MEMBERS.
6 [(g)] (H) (1) [An individual] A PERSON may not knowingly give false
7 information or make a material misstatement in an application required for any license
8 under this subtitle or in any supplemental information required by the Commission.
9 (2) [An individual] A PERSON who violates this section is guilty of a
10 misdemeanor and on conviction is subject to imprisonment not exceeding 3 years or a fine
11 not exceeding $5,000 or both.
12 9–1A–08.1.
13 (A) THE COMMISSION MAY NOT ISSUE A LICENSE TO A PERSON REQUIRED
14 TO BE LICENSED UNDER THIS SUBTITLE IF THE APPLICANT OR ANY OF THE
15 APPLICANT’S AFFILIATES, INCLUDING AN ENTITY UNDER COMMON CONTROL,
16 KNOWINGLY ACCEPTS REVENUE THAT IS DIRECTLY OR INDIRECTLY DERIVED FROM:
17 (1) A HIGH–RISK JURISDICTION SUBJECT TO A CALL FOR ACTION BY
18 THE FINANCIAL ACTION TASK FORCE;
19 (2) A JURISDICTION DESIGNATED AS A STATE SPONSOR OF
20 TERRORISM BY THE UNITED STATES; OR
21 (3) A JURISDICTION IN WHICH ONLINE CASINO GAMING IS
22 PROHIBITED AND THE REVENUE IS DERIVED FROM ONLINE CASINO GAMING IN THAT
23 JURISDICTION.
24 (B) (1) THE COMMISSION MAY NOT ALLOW A PERSON REQUIRED TO BE
25 LICENSED UNDER THIS SUBTITLE TO COMMENCE OR CONTINUE OPERATIONS IF THE
26 COMMISSION DETERMINES THAT THE PERSON OR ANY OF THE PERSON’S
27 AFFILIATES, INCLUDING ENTITIES UNDER COMMON CONTROL, KNOWINGLY
28 ACCEPTS REVENUE THAT IS DIRECTLY OR INDIRECTLY DERIVED FROM A
29 JURISDICTION DESCRIBED UNDER SUBSECTION (A) OF THIS SECTION.
30 (2) THE COMMISSION MAY REVOKE THE LICENSE OF A LICENSEE
31 THAT IS REQUIRED TO CEASE OPERATIONS UNDER PARAGRAPH (1) OF THIS
32 SUBSECTION IF, AFTER NOTICE AND OPPORTUNITY FOR A HEARING, THE
33 COMMISSION DETERMINES THAT IT WOULD FURTHER THE PUBLIC INTEREST TO
34 DISCONTINUE THE OPERATION OF THE LICENSEE IN THE STATE.

SENATE BILL 112 5
1 9–1E–03.
2 (a) (1) Unless the context requires otherwise, the requirements under §§
3 9–1A–04, 9–1A–06, 9–1A–07, 9–1A–08, 9–1A–08.1, 9–1A–12, 9–1A–14, 9–1A–18,
4 9–1A–19, 9–1A–20, and 9–1A–25 of this title apply to the authority, duties, and
5 responsibilities of the Commission, a sports wagering licensee, and an employee or a
6 contractor of a sports wagering licensee under this subtitle.
7 SECTION 2. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That this Act shall take effect July
8 1, 2026.

